===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[hurten#Middle English|hurten, hirten, hertan]]'' 'to injure, scathe, knock together', from {{etyl|xno}} ''[[hurter#Old French|hurter]]'' 'to ram into, strike, collide with' (compare French ''[[heurter#French|heurter]]'' 'to knock against, oppose'), ultimately from {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[hrutr#Old Norse|hrútr]]'' 'ram (male sheep)', lengthened-grade variant of {{term|hjǫrtr|lang=non|sc=Latinx}} 'stag',<ref>D.Q. Adams, ''Encyclopeida of Indo-European Culture'', s.v. "horn" (London: Fitzroy-Dearborn, 1999), 273.</ref> from *''xerutuz, xerutaz'' 'hart'. More at [[hart]].
Old French also gave Middle High German ''hurten'' and Dutch ''horten''.

Alternate etymology traces {{etyl|enm}} ''[[hurten#Middle English|hurten, hirten, hertan]]'' to {{etyl|ONF.}} ''[[hurter#Old French|hurter]]'' "to ram into, strike, collide with", of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|frk}} *{{term||hūrt|lang=frk}} "a battering ram" from {{proto|Germanic|hrūtanan|to fall, beat|lang=en}} from {{proto|Indo-European|krow-|to fall, beat, break|lang=en}}, also related to {{etyl|nl|-}} ''[[horten#Dutch|horten]]'' "to push against, strike", {{etyl|gml|-}} ''[[hurten#Middle Low German|hurten]]'' "to run at, collide with", {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[hrutr#Old Norse|hrūtr]]'' "battering ram".

===Verb===
{{en-verb|hurts|hurting|hurt}}

# {{intransitive}} To be [[painful]].
#: ''Does your leg still '''hurt'''? / It is starting to feel better.''
# {{transitive}} To cause (a creature) physical [[pain]] and/or [[injury]].
# {{transitive}} To cause (somebody) emotional [[pain]].

